Job Description:
In December 2018, Mayor de Blasio and New York City Housing Authority (NYCHA) released NYCHA 2.0, a comprehensive plan to fix and preserve public housing. NYCHA’s Real Estate Development Department (REDD) is charged with leading and structuring real estate transactions that intend address over $15 billion in capital needs. REDD primarily utilizes the following three tools to generate the necessary revenue for capital improvements:

1. Permanent Affordability Commitment Together (PACT) – PACT uses U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) Section 8 programs to fund renovations and convert public housing (Section 9) apartments to permanently affordable housing. NYCHA is in the process of converting 62,000 apartments over 10 years, which intends address $12.8 billion of capital needs.

2. Build to Preserve (BTP) – New mixed-income buildings will be constructed on some underutilized spaces across the NYCHA portfolio. NYCHA expects to address $2 billion in capital need across approximately 10,000 apartments.

3. Transfer to Preserve (TTP) – NYCHA will sell a portion of its estimated 80 million square feet of unused development rights (aka “air rights”) to adjacent privately-owned sites. TTP will generate $1 billion for capital repairs at adjacent developments.

Under the direction of the Design Director, the Urban Designer/Analyst will work on the implementation of a Design Excellence Program for PACT developments and other REDD projects. In doing so the Designer/Analyst will conduct complex and important research investigations, studies and examinations related to the physical design and planning of public housing. The Urban Designer/Analyst will prepare or supervise the preparation of drawings relating to the rehabilitation of public housing.

This is an exciting opportunity to join a small but growing team of real estate professionals, public housing experts, architects, planners, and urban designers to shape meaningful investments in NYCHA’s portfolio that not only address the physical needs of buildings and apartments but also enhance resident health and access to opportunity.

Key Responsibilities:

• Engage in the conduct of complex and important research investigations, studies or examinations related to the assessment of the physical design implications of NYCHA developments;
• Assist in the development and implementation of a Design Excellence Program for NYCHA PACT developments and other REDD projects;
• Research and implement best practices for renovations through the PACT program, including tenant-in-place strategies, re-cladding/over-cladding methods, refabricated/unitized construction components, materials, and property technology;
• Initiate urban design concepts such as NYCHA’s Connected Communities and other design guidelines;
• Assist with due diligence planning for new project sites including research and coordination of information related to existing capital needs, building systems, environmental conditions, and other property information;
• Supervise the preparation of drawings relating to urban design development studies for NYCHA and carries out urban design development studies;
• Assist with scope of work development for renovation projects including scoping and design consultants, development and review of RFPs for development partners, cost reasonableness/comparison, and Construction Document and Specification review;
• Assist with compliance related to waste, elevators, heating, and mold;
• Assist with implementation of energy and sustainability program measures and benchmarking, including compliance with NYC Building Code and applicable Local Laws;
• Create and deliver presentations to resident leaders, community stakeholders, elected officials, and NYCHA staff;
• Collaborate with City, State, and Federal agencies, as well as other NYCHA departments – including Capital Projects, Community Engagement & Partnerships, External Affairs, Operations, and Strategic Planning – to conduct research and develop strategies;
• Work with the REDD project team and development partners to ensure goals and strategies are appropriately implemented.

